Developed by Politecnico di Torino, EERI & PEER

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Try the Web version at:
https://www.edam.resiltronics.org

EDAM is an earthquake damage assessment manager developed by civil and computational engineers of the Politecnico di Torino in collaboration with the Pacific Earthquake Engineering Research Center (PEER), a department of the UC Berkeley directed by the professor Stephen A. Mahin, combining different damage evaluation forms from different countries worldwide such as Italy, US., New Zealand, Japan, Turkey etc.. The application can be used both by the public (residents) and by professionals who can collect earthquake damage data using also pictures, videos, sound records, etc.
Further information about the application can be found at the following address:

http://areeweb.polito.it/ricerca/ICRED/Software/EDAM.php

Refer to the following paper if you use the application:

Cimellaro, G. P., Scura, G., Renschler, C., Reinhorn, A. M., and Kim, H. (2014). "Rapid building damage assessment system using mobile phone technology" Earthquake Engineering and Engineering Vibration, 13(3), 519-533

Vallero, A., and Cimellaro, G. P. (2014). "EDAM: Earthquake damage assessment communication system using smartphones." Second European Conference on Earthquake Engineering and Seismology (2ECEES), Istanbul, August 24-29, 2014.
